- Um, better look in the manual.
- Ignorance.

262
00:15:22,254 --> 00:15:24,722
Wait a minute.
I know that woman.

263
00:15:24,823 --> 00:15:28,315
But from when?
And in what capacity?

264
00:15:28,427 --> 00:15:30,486
<i>It's her.!</i>

265
00:15:30,596 --> 00:15:33,326
- At last!
- This book must be out of date.

266
00:15:33,432 --> 00:15:36,492
I don't see Prussia,
Siam or autogiro.

267
00:15:36,602 --> 00:15:39,696
Keep looking!

268
00:15:43,509 --> 00:15:45,739
Are you sure this is the woman
you saw in the post office?

269
00:15:45,844 --> 00:15:48,335
Absolutely. Who could forget
such a monstrous visage?

270
00:15:48,447 --> 00:15:52,008
She has the sloping brow
and cranial bumpage of the career criminal.

271
00:15:52,117 --> 00:15:55,382
Uh, sir, phrenology was dismissed
as quackery 160 years ago.

272
00:15:55,487 --> 00:15:59,184
Of course you'd say that. You have
the brainpan of a stagecoach tilter.

273
00:15:59,291 --> 00:16:02,158
At any rate, the F.B.I. will track down
this mystery woman...

274
00:16:02,261 --> 00:16:04,889
and put her
behind bars.

275
00:16:06,198 --> 00:16:08,359
- How does it happen, Joe?
- How does what happen?

276
00:16:08,467 --> 00:16:10,526
How does a sweet young lady
mortgage her future...

277
00:16:10,636 --> 00:16:13,867
for a bunch of scraggly ideals
and greasy-haired promises?

278
00:16:13,973 --> 00:16:17,101
Maybe she thought the war in Southeast Asia
was so immoral her end justified the means.

279
00:16:17,209 --> 00:16:21,805
Gee, Joe. You haven't been the same
since your son went crazy in Vietnam.

280
00:16:21,914 --> 00:16:23,973
It's a pain that never ends.

281
00:16:35,594 --> 00:16:38,620
- Seven!
- No, Dad. It's a rhetorical question.

282
00:16:38,731 --> 00:16:40,358
Rhetorical, eh?

283
00:16:40,466 --> 00:16:43,492
- Eight!
- Dad, do you even know what "rhetorical" means?

284
00:16:43,602 --> 00:16:45,467
Do I know what
rhetorical means?

285
00:16:45,571 --> 00:16:48,563
<i>Quick, Grandma! Hide!</i>

286
00:16:53,846 --> 00:16:56,644
No door is gonna
keep me from my meddlin'!

287
00:16:56,749 --> 00:16:58,649
Stand up straight, Bart.

288
00:16:58,751 --> 00:17:00,548
Abe?

289
00:17:00,652 --> 00:17:02,984
What the-

290
00:17:03,088 --> 00:17:05,454
Now, here's a piece
of bad news.

291
00:17:05,557 --> 00:17:09,254
Oh, Abe!
You've aged terribly.

292
00:17:09,361 --> 00:17:13,024
What do you expect? You left me
to raise the boy on my own!

293
00:17:13,132 --> 00:17:16,260
I had to leave! But you didn't
have to tell Homer I was dead!

294
00:17:16,368 --> 00:17:21,067
It was either that or tell him
his mother was a wanted criminal!

295
00:17:21,173 --> 00:17:26,372
You were a rotten wife,
and I'll never ever forgive you!

296
00:17:27,946 --> 00:17:29,811
Can we have sex?
Please?

297
00:17:29,915 --> 00:17:33,146
- Oh, Abe!
- Well, I tried. What's for supper?

298
00:17:35,554 --> 00:17:38,717
Yeah. I might've seen her. It's hard to tell
from this old picture, you know?

299
00:17:38,824 --> 00:17:40,985
Well, according to
our computer-aging program...

300
00:17:41,093 --> 00:17:43,186
she should look about...

301
00:17:43,295 --> 00:17:44,790
25 years older.

302
00:17:50,569 --> 00:17:52,560
Yeah, I seen her. Uh,
that is to say, I saw her.

303
00:17:52,671 --> 00:17:55,071
Look at me, Grandma.
I'm a hippie. Peace, man.

304
00:17:55,174 --> 00:17:56,869
Groovy.
Bomb Vietnam!

305
00:17:56,975 --> 00:17:58,875
Four more years!
Up with people!

306
00:17:58,977 --> 00:18:01,810
You know, Grandma, I used to think
maybe I was adopted.

307
00:18:01,914 --> 00:18:04,348
I couldn't understand
how I fit into this family.

308
00:18:04,450 --> 00:18:08,716
Now that I've met you,
I suddenly make a lot of sense.

309
00:18:08,821 --> 00:18:14,726
I'm so glad to see the spirit of the '60s
is still alive in you kids.

310
00:18:23,335 --> 00:18:25,269
Yep.
I saw her.

311
00:18:25,370 --> 00:18:27,395
That is to say,
I seen her.

312
00:18:27,506 --> 00:18:29,235
She seemed like a nice lady.

313
00:18:29,341 --> 00:18:33,243
Well, that nice lady set the cause
of biological warfare back 30 years.

314
00:18:33,345 --> 00:18:35,313
We're only now
finally caught up.

315
00:18:35,414 --> 00:18:38,042
Two more ladies
come by earlier that day.

316
00:18:38,150 --> 00:18:41,347
One was real pretty.

317
00:18:41,453 --> 00:18:43,353
Tother, sort of plain.

318
00:18:45,791 --> 00:18:48,419
Ma'am, we're gonna need your assistance
